# jxl_phone_vs_desktop_rd_2026-05-26.tsv

Phase-1 probe: does targeting phone-perceived quality let JXL save
bits vs desktop-perceived quality? Pipeline (no encoder modification):

    cjxl-rs --effort 7 --distance D  ref.png -> out.jxl
    zenjxl-decoder-cli              out.jxl -> out.png
    cvvdp-gpu score_two_displays    (ref.png, out.png)
        -> JOD under standard_4k AND modern_oled_phone_indoor

Tools:
- encoder: ~/work/zen/jxl-encoder/target/release/cjxl-rs (prebuilt 2026-05-24)
- decoder: ~/work/zen/zenjxl-decoder/target/release/zenjxl-decoder-cli
- scorer:  crates/cvvdp-gpu/examples/score_two_displays.rs (CUDA, RTX 5070)
- harness: scripts/probes/phone_rd_probe.sh

Corpus: 5 eval refs (1024x768) spanning content classes:
  photo_general, photo_dark, lineart, photo_bright, screen_text
Distances (weighted toward aggressive end): 0.7 1.0 1.5 2.0 3.0 4.5 6.0 8.0

Displays:
- standard_4k            = desktop reference (200 nit, 75 ppd)
- modern_oled_phone_indoor = indoor SDR phone (400 nit auto-brightness
  setpoint, ~1000:1 effective contrast after 250 lux ambient washout,
  ~110 ppd at 0.35 m)

KEY FINDINGS:
- Phone is uniformly MORE forgiving (delta = jod_phone - jod_desktop
  >= 0 on every cell). Mechanism: ~1.5x ppd pushes pixel-scale
  compression artifacts up the cycles-per-degree axis past the CSF peak.
- Exploitable gap is CONCENTRATED in photographic content at aggressive
  compression: ~18-24% iso-quality byte savings on photo_general /
  photo_dark at JOD targets 9.5-9.7 (bpp 0.15-0.7).
- Non-photographic content (lineart, screen_text, photo_bright) shows
  ~0 gap — those stay near JOD 10 on both displays; no differentiation.
- photo_dark is FORGIVING here (+0.24 JOD at d8.0), NOT harsher. At the
  400-nit indoor auto-brightness setpoint the OLED's deep-black
  advantage is washed out by ambient, so the dark-sensitivity seen in
  the earlier 1025-nit iphone_14_pro panel-peak eval does not appear.
- At HIGH quality (bpp 1.5-2.7, distance <=1.5) deltas are tiny
  (+0.004 to +0.025 JOD) — the saving only materializes at the
  aggressive end (distance >=4, bpp <0.7).

CAVEAT (critical): a phone-targeted encode looks WORSE on a desktop at
75 ppd. The ~20% saving is only valid as a per-delivery-target encode
(gated on knowing the client is a high-DPR phone). The gap is captured
by the distance knob alone — it's a viewing-condition property, not a
codec-decision property. Whether a phone-AWARE encoder (targeted
high-freq relaxation via --epf / coarser high-band quant) can capture
the same saving with LESS desktop penalty is Phase 2 (not yet run).

NOTE: this is a directional PROBE on 5 images, NOT a calibration that
ships constants. A real calibration would need the full size x quality
x content coverage per the sweep-discipline rules.
